Event 7: {type:"encounter",trigger:"after_stop",triggerStop:1,title:"A Django Guide Appears",text:"A friendly guide meets your wagon. 'Django follows the MVT pattern — Model, View, Template. But newcomers from other frameworks get confused. In Django, what does the View do compared to MVC frameworks?'",choices:[{text:"The View handles request logic and picks which template to render — it's like the Controller in MVC",correct:true,explanation:"Exactly. Django's View is the controller. It receives the request, queries the model, and passes data to the template. Django's Template is the view layer. The naming is different from MVC, but the separation of concerns is the same."},{text:"The View is the HTML template that the user sees in the browser",correct:false,explanation:"That's the Template in Django. The naming confusion comes from MVC where 'view' means the visual layer. In Django, views are Python functions or classes that handle request logic."},{text:"The View is the database model that defines the data structure",correct:false,explanation:"That's the Model. The View sits between the Model and the Template — it fetches data from models and passes it to templates for rendering."}],concept:"Views and Request Handling",difficulty:"easy"}

Event 8: {type:"weather",trigger:"after_stop",triggerStop:2,title:"Admin Configuration Storm!",text:"A storm of admin requests hits your site. You registered your Post model with admin.site.register(Post) but the admin list shows only 'Post object (1)' for every entry. Users can't tell which post is which.",choices:[{text:"Add a __str__ method to the Post model that returns the title",correct:true,explanation:"Django's admin uses __str__ to display objects throughout the interface. Adding def __str__(self): return self.title gives every post a readable name. You can also customize the admin further with list_display, search_fields, and list_filter in a ModelAdmin class."},{text:"Override the admin template to show the title field directly",correct:false,explanation:"Overriding templates works but is far more complex than needed. The __str__ method is Django's standard way to give objects human-readable names, used everywhere — not just the admin."},{text:"Create a custom admin view that queries the title separately",correct:false,explanation:"A custom view for something this simple is massive overkill. Django's admin is designed to work with __str__ and ModelAdmin customization. One line in your model fixes this."}],concept:"ORM QuerySets",difficulty:"easy"}

Event 9: {type:"weather",trigger:"after_stop",triggerStop:4,title:"Migration Conflict!",text:"Two developers on your team both created migrations for the same model at the same time. Django is refusing to migrate with an 'Inconsistent migration history' error. Both migrations depend on the same parent.",choices:[{text:"Create a merge migration using python manage.py makemigrations --merge",correct:true,explanation:"Django can automatically create a merge migration that combines the two branches. The merge migration depends on both conflicting migrations, resolving the diamond dependency. This is the standard workflow for teams with concurrent model changes."},{text:"Delete one of the migrations and re-run makemigrations",correct:false,explanation:"Deleting a migration that's already been applied to other developers' databases or staging environments will cause drift between the code and the actual schema. The merge command exists precisely to handle this situation safely."},{text:"Manually edit one migration to depend on the other",correct:false,explanation:"Manually rewriting migration dependencies is fragile and error-prone. If the migrations modify the same fields, you could create an invalid sequence. The --merge flag handles the dependency graph correctly."}],concept:"ORM QuerySets",difficulty:"medium"}

Event 10: {type:"encounter",trigger:"after_stop",triggerStop:3,title:"A Signals Expert Appears",text:"A traveler shows you their code: when a new user registers, a Profile is automatically created using a post_save signal on the User model. 'Signals let models communicate without importing each other,' they explain. What is the main risk of overusing signals?",choices:[{text:"Signals create implicit control flow — it's hard to trace what happens when a model saves because listeners aren't visible in the calling code",correct:true,explanation:"Signals are powerful but invisible. When you call user.save(), there's no hint in that line of code that a Profile gets created, an email gets sent, or a cache gets invalidated. In large codebases, signal handlers become hidden side effects that make debugging extremely difficult."},{text:"Signals are slow because they use the database to send notifications between models",correct:false,explanation:"Signals are in-process Python function calls — they don't use the database at all. They're actually very fast. The concern isn't performance, it's maintainability and the hidden coupling they create."},{text:"Signals can only be used with built-in Django models, not custom ones",correct:false,explanation:"Signals work with any Django model, custom or built-in. You can even create your own custom signals. The concern is about code clarity, not capability limitations."}],concept:"Middleware Pipeline",difficulty:"medium"}

Event 11: {type:"misfortune",trigger:"after_stop",triggerStop:5,title:"Form Validation Bypass!",text:"A security report comes in: users are submitting forms with empty required fields. Your form class has the correct field definitions, but the view is calling form.save() without checking anything first.",choices:[{text:"Always check form.is_valid() before accessing cleaned_data or calling save",correct:true,explanation:"is_valid() runs all field validators, the clean method, and populates cleaned_data with sanitized values. Without it, you're saving raw, unvalidated input. Django forms are designed with a two-step pattern: validate first with is_valid(), then use the cleaned data."},{text:"Add HTML5 required attributes to the form fields so the browser validates",correct:false,explanation:"Client-side validation is easily bypassed with browser dev tools or curl. Server-side validation with is_valid() is the real defense. HTML5 attributes are a nice UX addition, but they're not a security boundary."},{text:"Use a try-except around form.save() to catch validation errors",correct:false,explanation:"By the time save() is called, it's too late — unvalidated data may have already been written. The is_valid() method is the gatekeeper that must run before any data processing."}],concept:"Views and Request Handling",difficulty:"easy"}

Event 12: {type:"river",trigger:"after_stop",triggerStop:6,title:"The Complex Query River",text:"You've reached a treacherous river. Your blog needs to find all posts that are either published by the current user OR published and in the 'news' category. A simple filter chain can't express OR conditions. How do you cross?",choices:[{text:"Use Q objects to combine conditions with the OR operator: Post.objects.filter(Q(author=user) | Q(status='published', category='news'))",correct:true,explanation:"Q objects let you build complex queries with AND, OR, and NOT operators. The pipe symbol means OR, the ampersand means AND, and the tilde means NOT. Without Q objects, Django's filter chain only supports AND conditions."},{text:"Run two separate queries and combine the results in Python with a set union",correct:false,explanation:"Two queries means two database round-trips, and combining in Python loses pagination, ordering, and database-level optimizations. Q objects generate a single SQL query with an OR clause — much more efficient."},{text:"Use raw SQL since Django's ORM can't handle OR conditions",correct:false,explanation:"Django's ORM handles OR conditions perfectly through Q objects. Raw SQL bypasses Django's protections and is harder to maintain. Q objects generate clean, efficient SQL while keeping your code Pythonic."}],concept:"ORM QuerySets",difficulty:"hard"}

Event 13: {type:"misfortune",trigger:"after_stop",triggerStop:3,title:"Database Connection Drought!",text:"Your Django app is crashing under load with 'too many connections' errors. Each request opens a new database connection, and your PostgreSQL server has hit its max_connections limit. The database is refusing new connections.",choices:[{text:"Configure CONN_MAX_AGE in DATABASES settings to reuse connections across requests instead of opening a new one each time",correct:true,explanation:"By default, Django opens and closes a database connection for every request. Setting CONN_MAX_AGE to a value like 600 (seconds) keeps connections alive and reusable. For high-traffic apps, use a connection pooler like PgBouncer for even better connection management."},{text:"Increase max_connections on the PostgreSQL server to allow more simultaneous connections",correct:false,explanation:"Raising the limit is a temporary fix. Each connection consumes server memory, and under heavy load you'll hit the new limit too. The real solution is connection reuse so you need fewer connections in the first place."},{text:"Switch to SQLite which doesn't have connection limits",correct:false,explanation:"SQLite has no connection pooling and uses file-level locking — it can only handle one write at a time. It's great for development but completely unsuitable for production traffic. The fix is connection reuse, not a different database."}],concept:"Middleware Pipeline",difficulty:"hard"}

